You can build a basic container in about 60 lines of Go by using Linux namespaces and cgroups. The process involves creating isolated processes, setting up a custom filesystem, and configuring network isolation. Here's a minimal example:

go
package main

import (
	"os"
	"os/exec"
)

func main() {
	cmd := exec.Command("sh")
	cmd.Stdin = os.Stdin
	cmd.Stdout = os.Stdout
	cmd.Stderr = os.Stderr
	cmd.SysProcAttr = &syscall.SysProcAttr{
		Cloneflags: syscall.CLONE_NEWUTS | syscall.CLONE_NEWPID | syscall.CLONE_NEWNS,
	}
	if err := cmd.Run(); err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}
}

This avoids simulating a full OS, instead focusing on process isolation and filesystem constraints.
